faq:
  - q: "What is the STAR method for behavioral interviews?"
    a: "STAR stands for Situation, Task, Action, Result. It is the standard framework for answering behavioral interview questions. Situation: set the context. Task: describe what you needed to accomplish. Action: explain what you specifically did. Result: share the measurable outcome. Senior-level answers add a fifth element — Consequence — what happened downstream for the team, product, or business as a result of your outcome."
  - q: "How many behavioral interview stories should I prepare?"
    a: "Prepare 6 to 8 reusable stories that can flex across multiple questions. Each story should cover a different theme: a technical tradeoff, execution under pressure, cross-functional conflict, leadership or influence, failure and recovery, and measurable business impact. With 6 to 8 strong stories, you can answer the 30 most common behavioral questions without repetition."
  - q: "What is a good example of a behavioral interview answer?"
    a: "A strong behavioral answer at the senior level names the constraint, explains the specific decision made and why, and quantifies the outcome. Example: 'We had 3 weeks to ship a feature that was blocking a $2M renewal. I made the call to descope the analytics dashboard and ship the core workflow only — which I communicated to the customer directly. We shipped on time, retained the account, and shipped the descoped feature 6 weeks later.' This is specific, decision-led, and result-focused."
  - q: "What is the most common behavioral interview question?"
    a: "Tell me about a time you faced a conflict with a coworker or stakeholder is consistently one of the most common. Others in the top 5: Tell me about a time you failed, Tell me about a challenge you overcame, Tell me about a time you led without authority, and Tell me about your greatest professional accomplishment. All five are best answered with the STAR method."
  - q: "How do behavioral interviews differ at senior vs. mid-level?"
    a: "Mid-level behavioral answers focus on individual execution — what you did and what happened. Senior-level answers focus on judgment under ambiguity, tradeoffs made, and second-order consequences. Interviewers at the senior level are evaluating whether you can operate with less oversight, make decisions under uncertainty, and own outcomes that affect teams and business metrics — not just tasks."
  - q: "How should I answer 'tell me about a time you failed'?"
    a: "Choose a real failure — not a disguised success. Describe what you decided, why it was the wrong call, what happened, and most importantly what you changed afterward. Strong answers at the senior level also address what the experience changed about how you make similar decisions now. Interviewers are evaluating self-awareness and learning velocity, not punishing imperfection."
howto:
  name: "How to Answer Behavioral Interview Questions Using STAR"
  steps:
    - name: "Prepare 6–8 reusable anchor stories"
      text: "Select stories that cover distinct themes: technical tradeoff, execution under pressure, cross-functional conflict, leadership or influence, failure and recovery, measurable business impact. Each story should be dense with specifics — team size, dollar amounts, timelines, decisions made."
    - name: "Structure each answer with STAR"
      text: "Situation (1 sentence of context), Task (what you needed to accomplish and why it mattered), Action (what you specifically decided and did — this should be 60% of your answer), Result (quantified outcome). For senior roles, add the downstream Consequence for the team or business."
    - name: "Lead with the decision, not the backstory"
      text: "Most candidates spend 60% of their answer on Situation and Task. Flip it — interviewers want to hear your reasoning and decision-making, not the setup. Get to the Action in 20–30 seconds."
    - name: "Quantify everything possible"
      text: "If you reduced churn, by how much? If you led a team, how large? If you shipped a feature, what was the business outcome? Numbers make stories credible and memorable. If exact numbers are unavailable, use approximations: 'roughly $2M', '8-person team', '30% improvement'."
    - name: "Practice out loud, not in your head"
      text: "Behavioral interviews are verbal. Reading your stories silently does not prepare you for speaking them under pressure. Record yourself or practice with a partner. Target 90–120 seconds per answer — concise enough to hold attention, long enough to be substantive."
